title: Grateful Dead Live at Winterland Arena on 1977-03-18
lineage: MAC > Nakamichi CR-7A > Audio Technica AM 400 Line Amp/mixer > Korg at 5.6 mhz > Audiogate > wav 24/96 - Transfer by Bob Menke; Lineage: Wav > iZotope RX6 Advanced > iZotope Ozone 5 Advanced > CD Wave > TLH > Flac 24; fixed version of source ID 140916
description:
Set 1

Promised Land, Mississippi Half Step, It's All Over Now, Sugaree, Minglewood Blues, Peggy-O, Cassidy, Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain

Set 2

Samson & Delilah, Brown Eyed Women, Good Lovin', Ship of Fools, Estimated Prophet, Terrapin Station-> Alhambra-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Saint Stephen-> Around & Around, E: Uncle John's Band

Note: First "Fire On The Mountain"

reviews.review_text: Great Audience This is one of the great ones; Allahmbra, First fire on the mountain, not to mention a HUGE not fade away that blue my mind!! I had this tape back in the Maxell XLII days. Special recording for me.

Very interesting show These March Winterland shows have a weird place in the 1977 canon. They continue to bust out some new material but sound a bit rusty at points (compared to 2/26/77). The first (Scarlet > ) Fire is great and the crowd LOVES the Scarlet reprise. The Alhambra is a bit tentative, like they aren't able to fully create the loping groove they want (it has a similar sound to Blues For Allah). The NFA is slow to build but is by far the highlight of the show. A strangely short St. Stephen ends the meat of the show and the Uncle John's bustout is an ok version that they do again the next night
